<BR><DIV CLASS="c4"><P CLASS="c8"><SPAN CLASS="c2">One aspect of the criminal justice system that has not received much attention after George Zimmerman was acquitted in the death of Trayvon Martin is the role that race may play in whether a death-by-firearm is ruled justifiable. Black Americans are far less likely to be adjudicated as justified in using deadly force in a firearm-related death. John Roman of the Urban Institute compiled the following figures from the Supplemental Homicide Reports submitted by local law enforcement to the FBI between 2005 to 2010. </SPAN></P>
